<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<speak version="1.1" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2001/10/synthesis">

<voice name="V2">
<prosody rate="95%" pitch="-2st">

Here is a truth that gets lost in the AI hype. <break time="400ms"/> Building a model is only half the job.

<break time="600ms"/>

The other half is <emphasis level="moderate">deployment</emphasis>. <break time="300ms"/> Getting the model from a notebook into production. <break time="300ms"/> Running it reliably and securely at scale. <break time="300ms"/> Integrating it with systems that run the business.

<break time="600ms"/>

This is where most AI projects stall. <break time="300ms"/> Not because the model does not work. <break time="300ms"/> Because deployment is hard. <break time="300ms"/> Integration is harder.

<break time="700ms"/>

Agentic AI makes this more challenging. <break time="300ms"/> Agents call tools. <break time="200ms"/> They access data. <break time="200ms"/> They interact with enterprise systems. <break time="400ms"/> The deployment model you choose determines what is possible.

<break time="600ms"/>

This module is about those choices.

<break time="1200ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Deployment Models.

<break time="500ms"/>

Let us start with deployment models.

<break time="500ms"/>

Definition: A deployment model defines where your AI runs, who operates it, and what infrastructure supports it.

<break time="500ms"/>

There are four primary models.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">SaaS</emphasis>: Vendor-Hosted AI.

<break time="400ms"/>

You access AI through a third-party service. <break time="300ms"/> You call an API. <break time="200ms"/> The vendor runs the infrastructure.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: velocity. <break time="300ms"/> SaaS is the fastest path to production.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: you are subject to vendor rate limits, latency, and pricing. <break time="300ms"/> Your data goes to their servers.

<break time="400ms"/>

Failure mode: compliance issues with data residency.

<break time="600ms"/>

Cloud GPU Rental.

<break time="400ms"/>

You run your own inference on rented cloud GPUs. <break time="300ms"/> AWS, GCP, or Azure instances. <break time="300ms"/> You control configuration but do not own hardware.

<break time="400ms"/>

For engineers: this model offers scaling flexibility.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: costs escalate quickly at scale.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">On-Premises</emphasis>.

<break time="400ms"/>

You run AI on infrastructure you own. <break time="300ms"/> Hardware in your data center. <break time="300ms"/> Full control of GPUs, network, and software.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: data sovereignty. <break time="300ms"/> Some industries require data to never leave organizational infrastructure.

<break time="400ms"/>

For product and technical leaders: on-prem requires capital expenditure and operational team.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: upgrades require planning.

<break time="600ms"/>

Hybrid and <emphasis level="moderate">Edge</emphasis>.

<break time="400ms"/>

Hybrid combines cloud and on-prem. <break time="300ms"/> Train in cloud, deploy on-prem. <break time="300ms"/> Or primary inference in cloud with on-prem fallback.

<break time="400ms"/>

Edge deployment pushes inference to devices at the network edge. <break time="300ms"/> Robots. <break time="200ms"/> Vehicles. <break time="200ms"/> Industrial equipment.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: latency. <break time="300ms"/> Edge minimizes network round trips.

<break time="600ms"/>

Each model is a choice about control, cost, compliance, and capability.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Integration Surfaces.

<break time="500ms"/>

Deployment is only half the challenge. <break time="300ms"/> The other half is integration.

<break time="500ms"/>

An agentic system that cannot connect to enterprise data is useless.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: <emphasis level="moderate">Integration surfaces</emphasis> are the interfaces that connect agents to enterprise systems.

<break time="600ms"/>

API Integrations.

<break time="400ms"/>

The most common integration surface. <break time="300ms"/> Your agent calls external APIs to retrieve data and execute actions.

<break time="400ms"/>

For engineers: API integration requires authentication, error handling, and rate limiting.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: it is not just about making calls. <break time="300ms"/> It is about making calls reliably.

<break time="600ms"/>

Tool Interfaces.

<break time="400ms"/>

For agentic systems, tools are specialized integrations.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: A tool is a function the agent can invoke. <break time="300ms"/> SQL queries. <break time="200ms"/> Code execution. <break time="200ms"/> Knowledge base search. <break time="200ms"/> Email sending.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: actionability. <break time="300ms"/> Tools bridge reasoning and reality.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">Data Connectors</emphasis>.

<break time="400ms"/>

Agents need access to structured data. <break time="300ms"/> Databases. <break time="200ms"/> Data warehouses. <break time="200ms"/> Document repositories.

<break time="400ms"/>

For engineers: vector database connectors are essential for retrieval workflows.

<break time="600ms"/>

<emphasis level="moderate">Policy Gateways</emphasis>.

<break time="400ms"/>

In enterprise environments, not all actions are permitted.

<break time="400ms"/>

Definition: Policy gateways enforce rules about what agents can access and what requires approval.

<break time="400ms"/>

For product and technical leaders: policy gateways integrate with identity systems and compliance engines.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: governance.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Matching Deployment to Business Drivers.

<break time="500ms"/>

Let us connect deployment and integration to business drivers.

<break time="500ms"/>

SaaS for Velocity. <break time="300ms"/> Startups and innovation teams choose SaaS because it is fast. <break time="300ms"/> Working prototype in days.

<break time="400ms"/>

Constraint: locked into vendor capabilities and pricing.

<break time="500ms"/>

Cloud for Flexibility. <break time="300ms"/> Teams needing custom models choose cloud GPU rental. <break time="300ms"/> Control without capital expense.

<break time="400ms"/>

For engineers: cloud is default for variable workloads.

<break time="500ms"/>

On-Prem for Compliance. <break time="300ms"/> Regulated industries choose on-premises. <break time="300ms"/> The driver is control, not cost.

<break time="400ms"/>

Enterprise driver: data cannot leave organizational infrastructure.

<break time="500ms"/>

Edge for Latency. <break time="300ms"/> Industrial applications use edge inference. <break time="300ms"/> When network latency is unacceptable.

<break time="600ms"/>

Enterprise Blockers.

<break time="400ms"/>

Deployment decisions are not just technical. <break time="300ms"/> They are organizational.

<break time="400ms"/>

Failure mode: procurement friction slowing hardware acquisition.

<break time="300ms"/>

Failure mode: compliance requirements limiting cloud options.

<break time="300ms"/>

Failure mode: integration debt with legacy systems.

<break time="500ms"/>

For product and technical leaders: adoption is about risk, cost, and organizational readiness.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="100%">

Section: Certification Alignment.

<break time="500ms"/>

The certification expects you to understand deployment models and integration surfaces.

<break time="500ms"/>

Expect questions matching deployment models to business requirements. <break time="300ms"/> Data sovereignty means on-premises. <break time="300ms"/> Rapid iteration means SaaS.

<break time="500ms"/>

This aligns with NVIDIA exam domains around deployment contexts and integration architecture.

<break time="500ms"/>

Know the tradeoffs. <break time="300ms"/> Cloud offers flexibility but ongoing cost. <break time="300ms"/> On-prem offers control but requires capital. <break time="300ms"/> SaaS offers speed but limited customization.

<break time="500ms"/>

The certification also covers operational concerns. <break time="300ms"/> SLAs. <break time="200ms"/> Monitoring. <break time="200ms"/> Evaluation. <break time="200ms"/> Update processes.

<break time="500ms"/>

Understand why integration matters for agents specifically. <break time="300ms"/> Agents need tools. <break time="200ms"/> Tools require integration.

<break time="800ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

<voice name="V1">
<prosody rate="98%">

Section: Key Takeaways.

<break time="600ms"/>

Deployment models define where AI runs. <break time="300ms"/> SaaS, cloud, on-prem, or edge.

<break time="500ms"/>

Integration surfaces connect agents to the enterprise. <break time="300ms"/> APIs. <break time="200ms"/> Tools. <break time="200ms"/> Data connectors. <break time="200ms"/> Policy gateways.

<break time="500ms"/>

Business drivers shape deployment choices. <break time="300ms"/> Velocity. <break time="200ms"/> Flexibility. <break time="200ms"/> Compliance. <break time="200ms"/> Latency.

<break time="500ms"/>

Deployment is where AI becomes real. <break time="300ms"/> It is where models become systems.

<break time="500ms"/>

Know the models. <break time="200ms"/> Know the surfaces. <break time="200ms"/> Know how to match them to requirements.

<break time="600ms"/>

This is the bridge from architecture to operations.

<break time="1000ms"/>

</prosody>
</voice>

</speak>
